Target: `module/LLMWorkflow/retrieval/CaveatRegistry.ps1`

Reason:
- surface meaningful cleanup failures in atomic registry writes
- avoid a hidden operational residue path when registry save fails after temp file creation
- tighten one custom-caveat edge case that can read a missing `packs` member unsafely

---

## Patch A: surface temp-file cleanup failure in `Save-CaveatRegistryInternal`

Current code:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file on failure
    if (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempPath) {
        Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempPath -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
    }
    throw "Failed to save caveat registry: $_"
}
```

Replace with:

```powershell
catch {
    # Clean up temp file on failure
    if ($tempPath -and (Test-Path -LiteralPath $tempPath)) {
        try {
            Remove-Item -LiteralPath $tempPath -Force -ErrorAction Stop
        }
        catch {
            Write-Warning "[CaveatRegistry] Failed to remove temporary registry file '$tempPath' after save failure: $($_.Exception.Message)"
        }
    }
    throw "Failed to save caveat registry: $_"
}
```

Why this matters:
- a failed registry save already represents degraded state
- silently leaking temp files makes later diagnostics worse and hides filesystem or permission issues

## Patch B: guard missing `packs` member in `Find-ApplicableCaveats`

Current code:

```powershell
if (-not $packMatch -and $caveat.triggers.packs.Count -gt 0 -and $packsUsed.Count -gt 0) {
    continue
}
```

Replace with:

```powershell
$triggerPacks = @()
if ($caveat.triggers.ContainsKey('packs') -and $null -ne $caveat.triggers.packs) {
    $triggerPacks = @($caveat.triggers.packs)
}

if (-not $packMatch -and $triggerPacks.Count -gt 0 -and $packsUsed.Count -gt 0) {
    continue
}
```

Why this matters:
- predefined caveats are mostly safe, but custom/imported caveats can omit `packs`
- this avoids a null/member access edge case in a registry that is designed to be extensible

